(185, '2011-09-15 12:32:49', 'Chapter 1:\r\n\r\nThe year is 2162, and our Sun is becoming unstable.  The Sun''s life cycle has reached a point in its life cycle where the Fusion reaction at the core of the yellow sun is slowing down, and as a compensation the the star transforms into a red giant.  The sun''s red giant is expected to grow in diameter so large it will consume the planets Mercury, Venus, Earth, and Mars.  It will be the end of Human life. \r\n\r\nThe one thing which could restart the fusion reaction and keep the Sun burning hot as a yellow sun would be to turn Venus into a large fusion reaction which would turn it into a small star. Then with some force the new Venus star would have to be collided with the Sun.  This would cause the Sun to re-energize and burn hot for another calculated 1 Million years.  But the effort to do this would take all of man kind''s energy and focus to pull of a reaction of this measure.  Putting a man to the moon would be like a small step for man kind compared to the giant leap saving the sun would be.', '', 1, '/files/Literature/Red Sun', NULL, 0),
