(437, '2012-12-31 22:51:05', 'Here is a video of my first attempt at a perminate magnate motor. I developed this magnet motor (which does not work) from some actual physical calculations.', 'WP_20121224_215023Z.mp4', 1, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 3778664, 0),
(438, '2013-01-01 15:45:08', 'The physical calculations I performed was quite the approximation with partical physics.  But what I have attached here is the code I thought was complete, but turned out to be erroneous..  This is why I might have thought that this was possible, but I will post the corrected code next.  And you see what you would expect in the corrected code (No net force).', 'MagCalcsError.xlsm', 1, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 162124, 0),
(439, '2013-01-01 15:48:26', 'Here is the corrected MagMotor Calculations...', 'MagCalcs.xlsm', 1, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 161432, 0),
(441, '2013-01-01 16:01:47', 'Interestingly enough, I had thought that what other people had presented with an angled magnet may make it possible to have a net torque, but in the excel sheet with the error it showed that no angle was the most optimal, so I gave up on the idea that you need to angle the magnets. But it is seen in the corrected partical physics model that the angled magnets do give a net torque. So what is the optimal angle.. Well the spread sheet can tell you this.', 'magmotor.jpg', 1, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 10043, 0),
(442, '2013-01-01 16:05:24', 'One thing to note about the magmotor spread sheet, is that it is much a simplification to the real physics of a magnet.  It is approximating the magnet as dipole particles and their force fields are each radial from the magnet nodes.  So believe it as you may.', '', 1, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 0, 0),
