(445, '2013-01-02 18:42:14', 'one concern I had with the current implementation is that you are going to generate crazy eddy currents in the aluminum stator/rotor that will sap all of the additional energy in your system. Notice how most setups use non conducting materials like in the pic you posted with the arrangement on a wooden table, granted the CD has a thin metallic deposition that may have some negative effect. I like the discovery of having to increase the spacing between your stator and rotor; i think the inertia in the rotor will be critical to carrying it through repulsive field and into repelling field where it will pick up additional energy. Its like pressing bumps on skis. One quick way to try to clarify the B fields is to use smaller magnets, like the disc kind instead of oblong.', '', 62, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 0, 0),
(446, '2013-01-09 03:37:28', 'Hey ewyman87! So I love your comment.  You are probably right about all of that, it is positively interesting to think that there may be a way to make this motor work or a motor like it work.  I unfortunately have in my experimentation of the possiblity of a perminate magnet motor have decided it is not going to be an easy road to make this work. I thought with the revelation shown with the simple particle physics model that it could work; so I built it.  But the feeling as I experiment that the \\"getting over the hump\\" of the repulsive (to rotation) force fields to get to the attracting (to rotation)force is not easy; maybe inertia is the key.\r\nWith all the videos online and people really working on this technology it may be a future viable clean energy source, I just don\\''t think now that it is going to be as simple as I have taken the problem to be.  But with a website like CirrusIdea maybe the collective can make it work.  I\\''ll post the solid models I used, so if anyone wants to continue this work please do, because you could change the world with a technology in concept that this is.', '', 1, '/files/Energy Solutions/MagnaMotor', 0, 0),
